@Priscilla Lee 
I like that you drew attention to the scale. The percentages range from just below 80% to almost 100%. What do those percentages mean?  What percentage should states be targeting? 

I also wondered about Mississippi--they were close to full vaccination before the pandemic and still are above the rate recommended to prevent outbreaks!

@JaeMin Yu 
I am also curious about what might be behind the differences between states with vaccination rates that have declined since the pandemic versus those that have stayed the same or gone up. I did a bit more reading and found that although recommended vaccination rates to prevent outbreaks are provided by federal agencies, states set their own policies about exemptions and enforcement.

What policies does your state have around vaccinations for children attending public schools?

@Tessa 
You noticed that the percent of kindergarteners that have been vaccinated for the measles has dropped since the pandemic for most states. Why do you think less parents are getting their children vaccinated? 

You also noted that your state has had a significant decrease in the percent of kindergarteners vaccinated.   How do the current vaccination rates in your state compare to neighboring states?
